def convert_to_inches(height):
    if isinstance(height, float):
        return height
    feet, inches = map(int, height.replace('"', '').split("'"))
    total_inches = (feet * 12) + inches
    return float(total_inches)
In [18]:

10. Finding Ouliers and capping them with upper limit and lower limit¶

In [32]:
Q1 = df['age'].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df['age'].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1
lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5*IQR
upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5*IQR

outliers = (df['age'] < lower_bound) | (df['age'] > upper_bound)
outliers.value_counts()

a) Finding a optimal K value using elbow plot¶

In [47]:
# creating an emoty list to store sum of squared distances(SSD)
ssd = []

#Define a range of k values to try
k_values = range(1,13) #adjust as needed

#perform k-means clustering for each k and compute ssd
for k in k_values:
    clusters= KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=100)
    clusters.fit(pca_df)
    ssd.append(clusters.inertia_)
In [48]:
cluster_df = pd.DataFrame({'k': k_values, 'ssd': ssd})
In [49]:
plt.plot(k_values, ssd, marker='o', linestyle='-')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters (K)')
plt.ylabel('Sum of Squared Distances (SSD)')
plt.title('Elbow Method for Optimal K')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
  • we can see a clear elbow at 2, so taking k as 2.
